WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.400
6.0 English From BBCLearningEnglish.com

2
00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:12.400
Hello, this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

3
00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:20.400
And I'm Georgie. If you ask a woman, are you eating food too? The phrase has a very specific meaning.

4
00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:29.800
You're asking, are you pregnant? And like many of the idioms we commonly use in English, this phrase contains a little bit of truth.

5
00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:36.600
A pregnant woman really is eating food too, herself and the baby growing inside her.

6
00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:46.800
The female human body is amazing. During pregnancy it protects the growing baby by allowing it to take whatever nutrients it needs from the mother.

7
00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:52.800
This means it's the mum to be, not the baby, who experiences any nutritional problems.

8
00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:57.800
It's also the reason why it's so important that pregnant women eat well.

9
00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:04.800
In this program, we'll be finding out how a woman's relationship to food changes during pregnancy.

10
00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:09.800
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary too.

11
00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:18.800
But first, I have a question for you Phil. For some pregnant women, finding reliable information on what food to eat can be hard.

12
00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.800
Finding out about harmful foods to avoid on the other hand is much easier.

13
00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:35.800
So, according to NHS recommendations, which of these foods should pregnant women not eat? Is it a, chips? B, oily fish or C, smoked salmon?

14
00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:38.800
I think the answer is C, smoked salmon.

15
00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:43.800
Okay Phil, we'll find out the correct answer at the end of the program.

16
00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:52.800
Although eating healthy and nutritious food is important for mum's and babies, the story gets complicated because of the changes a woman's body goes through during pregnancy.

17
00:01:52.800 --> 00:02:01.800
Here's Jaguoway's presenter of BBC Radio 4's, the Food Program, reporting on her experience of pregnancy.

18
00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:10.800
I feel like throughout this pregnancy, my body is just a bit haywire, and there are things that my body is doing.

19
00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:12.800
That's frankly weird.

20
00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:15.800
Noesbleeds are really good example.

21
00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:22.800
I can count the amount of nosebleeds pre-pregnancy I've had on one hand, and now I seem to get them all the time.

22
00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:28.800
Jaguoway says that during pregnancy her body went haywire. It stopped working properly.

23
00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:36.800
For example, she had lots of nosebleeds, whereas before being pregnant, she could count the number of nosebleeds she had on one hand.

24
00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:46.800
The idiom to count the number of something on one hand emphasizes that this doesn't happen very often, or that there's a small number of something.

25
00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:50.800
After all, you can only count a five on one hand.

26
00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:58.800
Many pregnant women experience cravings. The strong desire for some particular food, anything from ice cream to sardines.

27
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:08.800
When these cravings offer food that's not so healthy, some women feel guilty, thinking I know I should be eating healthy, but all I want is chips.

28
00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:16.800
Here's Jaguoway's again, speaking with nutritional therapist Henrietta Wilson, on the best way to deal with guilty feelings.

29
00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.800
How guilty should you feel?

30
00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:23.800
It's more the question for that late night chocolate binge.

31
00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:27.800
When your body is telling you, you are need cake.

32
00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:33.800
Listen, I think the most important thing is to not get out the cast of nine tails, is to absolutely be kind to yourself.

33
00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:42.800
Particularly in that first trimester, it is a very critical window, but at the same time it can be the time when all you want to do is to eat chips.

34
00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:47.800
Because your body is going through what it perceives to be physiological stress.

35
00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:52.800
So it's doing the best that you can and it's absolutely not about giving yourself a hard time.

36
00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:56.800
Jaguoway's food cravings led to a chocolate binge.

37
00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:03.800
A binge is an occasion where you do something in an extreme way, like eating or drinking too much.

38
00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:07.800
Henrietta's advice is to not use the catarine tails.

39
00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:13.800
In the past, the catarine tails was a whip made of nine strings which was used to punish prisoners.

40
00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:22.780
Nowadays, when someone talks about the catarine tails, they are probably talking about the ways people sometimes use to punish themselves if they're not

41
00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:23.780
a good.

42
00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:31.780
But says Henrietta, pregnancy isn't about giving yourself a hard time treating itself badly or criticizing yourself.

43
00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:34.780
Pregnancy is a special time of life.

44
00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:38.780
An older baby can ask is that mum does her best.

45
00:04:38.780 --> 00:04:49.780
And of course, avoid some foods, which reminds me if your question, Georgie, which food does the NHS recommend pregnant women do not eat?

46
00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:51.780
I guess it was smoked salmon.

47
00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:54.780
Which was the correct answer.

48
00:04:54.780 --> 00:05:00.780
Smoked salmon is best avoided because of the risk of bacteria, but oily fish is good.

49
00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:03.780
And even a bowl of chips now and then are fine.

50
00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:07.780
Right, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in the program.

51
00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:11.780
Starting with the idiom eating for two, which means to be pregnant.

52
00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:17.780
If something goes haywire, it stops working properly or becomes difficult to control.

53
00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:26.780
If you say you could count something on one hand, you're emphasizing that something does not happen very often, or that there are only a few of those things.

54
00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.780
A binge is an occasion when you do something to access.

55
00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:34.780
For example, eat, drink or spend money.

56
00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:45.780
In the past, the catarine tails was a whip used to punish prisoners, but nowadays it usually refers to the ways in which someone criticises themselves as a form of self-punishment.

57
00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:53.780
And finally, to give yourself a hard time, means to treat yourself badly by criticising or blaming yourself.

58
00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:56.780
Once again, ask six minutes of up.

59
00:05:56.780 --> 00:06:03.780
Remember to join us again next time for more topical discussion and useful vocabulary here at six minute English.

60
00:06:03.780 --> 00:06:04.780
Goodbye for now.

61
00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:05.780
Bye!

